  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary to-primary-light py-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 text-center text-white">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold mb-4 text-white">Starting Your First Job in New Zealand: IRD Number, Tax Code & KiwiSaver</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-white/90">A step-by-step guide for new workers in New Zealand, from getting an IRD number to reading your first payslip.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="mb-8 text-sm text-text-muted">
        <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 flex-wrap">
          <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Home</a></li>
          <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-2 before:text-border"><a href="/guides/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Guides</a></li>
          <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-2 before:text-border font-medium text-text">Starting Your First Job in NZ</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          Starting your first job in New Zealand is an exciting milestone, whether you are a school leaver, a recent graduate, or a migrant arriving in Aotearoa for the first time. Alongside learning the ropes at work, there are several administrative steps you need to complete to ensure you are set up correctly with Inland Revenue (IRD), your employer's payroll, and KiwiSaver. Getting these things right from day one saves hassle later and ensures your pay is correct from your very first payslip.
        </p>

        <p>
          This guide walks you through everything you need to do before and during your first weeks of employment, including obtaining an IRD number, choosing the correct tax code, understanding automatic KiwiSaver enrolment, setting up your bank account for pay, and decoding your first payslip. Think of this as your complete checklist for a smooth start to working life in New Zealand.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Step 1: Get an IRD Number</h2>

        <p>
          An IRD number is your unique tax identification number in New Zealand. You need one before you can start working legally and receiving the correct tax treatment on your pay. Every person who earns income in New Zealand must have an IRD number. It is an eight or nine digit number assigned by Inland Revenue, and you keep the same number for life.
        </p>

        <p>
          You can apply for an IRD number online through the IRD website at ird.govt.nz. The online application requires a valid form of identification, which for New Zealand citizens or residents is typically a New Zealand passport, driver licence, or birth certificate. For migrants, you will need your passport and evidence of your visa or immigration status. The application is free and processing usually takes around 8 to 10 working days, though it can be faster if you apply online with all the correct documents.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you prefer to apply in person, you can visit an AA Driver Licensing agent with your identification documents. You can also apply by post using the IRD number application form (IR742 for individuals). However, the online method is the fastest and most convenient.
        </p>

        <p>
          It is important to apply for your IRD number as early as possible, ideally before you start your job. Without an IRD number, your employer will deduct tax at the no-notification rate of 45 percent, which is significantly higher than the normal rates. While you will get any over-deduction back as a refund at the end of the tax year, it reduces your take home pay in the meantime.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Step 2: Choose Your Tax Code</h2>

        <p>
          When you start a new job, your employer will give you a Tax code declaration form (IR330) to complete. This form asks for your IRD number and the tax code you wish to use. For your first job, the correct tax code is usually M (primary employment) or ME (primary employment with the Independent Earner Tax Credit, if your expected income is between $24,000 and $48,000 and you do not receive any government benefits).
        </p>

        <p>
          If you have a student loan from a previous period of study, your tax code should include the letters SL, making it MSL or MESL. This tells your employer to deduct student loan repayments from your pay alongside PAYE tax. If you are unsure about your tax code, IRD provides a helpful online tool called the tax code finder on their website.
        </p>

        <p>
          It is crucial to complete the IR330 and return it to your employer promptly, ideally before your first payday. If your employer does not have your tax code declaration by the time they process your first pay, they are required to use the no-notification rate of 45 percent, which will take a large chunk out of your earnings.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Step 3: Understand KiwiSaver Enrolment</h2>

        <p>
          When you start a new job in New Zealand, your employer is required to automatically enrol you in KiwiSaver, the country's workplace retirement savings scheme. This applies if you are aged between 18 and 64, are a New Zealand citizen or hold a visa that permits you to work, and are employed for more than 28 days. Your employer will begin deducting KiwiSaver contributions from your pay at the default rate of 3 percent of your gross earnings.
        </p>

        <p>
          You have choices to make about your KiwiSaver membership. First, you can choose your contribution rate: 3, 4, 6, 8, or 10 percent. If you do not choose, 3 percent is applied by default. Second, you can choose your KiwiSaver provider and fund type. If you do not choose a provider within a certain timeframe, your employer will enrol you in their default scheme or you may be assigned to a government-appointed default provider.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you decide you do not want to be in KiwiSaver, you have an opt-out window between the 14th and 56th day after starting employment. To opt out, complete a KiwiSaver opt-out request form (KS10) and give it to your employer. Any contributions already deducted will be refunded. However, think carefully before opting out, because you will miss out on the employer's minimum 3 percent contribution and the government's annual contribution of up to $521.43. Most financial advisors recommend staying in KiwiSaver even at the minimum rate.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Step 4: Set Up Your Bank Account</h2>

        <p>
          Your employer will need your bank account details to deposit your pay. If you do not already have a New Zealand bank account, you will need to open one before your first payday. Most New Zealand banks offer everyday transaction accounts with no fees, and you can typically open an account online or by visiting a branch.
        </p>

        <p>
          To open a bank account, you will need identification (passport, driver licence, or birth certificate) and proof of address (such as a utility bill, tenancy agreement, or letter from your employer). Some banks have specific requirements for new migrants, so check with your chosen bank beforehand. Popular banks in New Zealand include ANZ, ASB, BNZ, Kiwibank, and Westpac.
        </p>

        <p>
          You also need a bank account for IRD, as this is where any tax refunds will be deposited. You can link your bank account to your IRD profile through myIR, IRD's online portal. Setting up myIR early is a good idea, as it gives you access to your tax records, KiwiSaver information, student loan balance, and more.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Step 5: Know Your Employment Rights</h2>

        <p>
          As a new employee in New Zealand, you have important legal rights from day one. These include the right to be paid at least the minimum wage (currently $23.15 per hour as of April 2025 for adult workers), the right to a written employment agreement, rest breaks and meal breaks during your shift, four weeks of annual leave after 12 months of employment, five days of sick leave after six months of employment (increasing to 10 days per year), and public holiday entitlements.
        </p>

        <p>
          Your employer must provide you with a written employment agreement before you start work. This agreement sets out the terms of your employment, including your pay rate, hours of work, leave entitlements, and the process for resolving any employment relationship problems. Read your agreement carefully before signing, and do not hesitate to ask questions about anything you do not understand. Employment New Zealand provides free resources and advice on employment rights at employment.govt.nz.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Understanding Your First Payslip</h2>

        <p>
          Your first payslip can be a bit of a shock if you have never seen one before. The difference between your gross pay (total earnings before deductions) and your net pay (the amount deposited into your bank account) can be significant. Here is a breakdown of what you will typically see:
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Gross Pay:</strong> This is your total earnings for the pay period, calculated from your hourly rate times hours worked, or your annual salary divided by the number of pay periods. <strong>PAYE Tax:</strong> The income tax deducted using the progressive brackets based on your tax code. <strong>ACC Earner's Levy:</strong> Currently 1.60 percent of your gross pay, which funds New Zealand's universal accident compensation scheme. <strong>KiwiSaver Employee Contribution:</strong> Your chosen contribution rate (3 percent by default) deducted from gross pay. <strong>Student Loan Repayment:</strong> If applicable, 12 percent on income above the weekly threshold. <strong>Net Pay:</strong> What is left after all deductions, the amount deposited into your bank account.
        </p>

        <p>
          You may also see your employer's KiwiSaver contribution noted on the payslip, though this is not a deduction from your pay. It is an additional amount your employer pays into your KiwiSaver account. Some payslips also show year-to-date totals, which track your cumulative earnings and deductions for the tax year.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Example: First-Job Take Home Pay</h2>

        <p>
          Let us work through an example for someone starting their first full-time job at $50,000 per year with a 3 percent KiwiSaver contribution and no student loan. The annual deductions would be approximately: PAYE tax of $7,420, ACC Earner's Levy of $800, and KiwiSaver employee contribution of $1,500. This gives a total annual deduction of approximately $9,720, leaving a take home pay of about $40,280 per year, or approximately $1,549 per fortnight.
        </p>

        <p>
          Use our <a href="/" class="text-accent hover:underline">salary calculator</a> to work out the exact figures for your salary level and chosen KiwiSaver rate. Knowing your expected take home pay before you start helps you plan your budget for rent, groceries, transport, and other living expenses.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Setting Up myIR</h2>

        <p>
          myIR is Inland Revenue's online portal and is your central hub for managing all your tax affairs. Through myIR, you can view your tax code, check your income and tax deduction records, see your student loan balance, manage your KiwiSaver membership, view and respond to tax assessments, and update your contact and bank account details. Setting up myIR early in your working life is highly recommended. You can register at ird.govt.nz using your IRD number and email address.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Tips for New Workers in New Zealand</h2>

        <p>
          First, keep records of all your pay-related documents, including your employment agreement, payslips, tax code declarations, and KiwiSaver information. Digital copies are fine. Second, check your payslip each pay period to make sure your hours, pay rate, and deductions are correct. Mistakes happen, and catching them early is much easier than sorting them out later. Third, start budgeting from day one. Knowing your net pay allows you to plan for essential expenses and set savings goals. Fourth, if you are eligible for the IETC, make sure you are using the ME tax code to receive the tax credit throughout the year rather than waiting for a refund. Fifth, consider choosing a higher KiwiSaver rate if you can afford it, as the difference compounds significantly over decades.
        </p>

        <!-- FAQ Section -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

